# Core Standards

Use these defaults for all work unless a more specific scoped rule applies.

## Priority Order

1. Correctness and safety
2. Clear architecture boundaries
3. Readability and maintainability
4. Performance and efficiency

## Engineering Defaults

- Resolve root causes instead of patching symptoms.
- Keep functions focused on one responsibility; split mixed concerns.
- Prefer reusable helpers for repeated logic instead of copy-paste.
- Use clear names and straightforward control flow.
- Add brief comments only where intent is non-obvious.
- Keep files reasonably lean; split when a file grows hard to navigate.

## Collaboration and Traceability

- **CPPR / CPPRD:** code changes that ship via PR should follow **CPPR** (commit, push, pull request). For accountability in this workspace, follow **CPPRD** (add **D**ocumentation): a durable summary in subrepo `CHANGELOG`, `deploy/`, or `design_docs/` as appropriate — see `deploy/CPPR_AND_CPPRD.md`.
- Check the relevant local docs and design notes before major changes.
- Update the relevant changelog or tracking docs when behavior changes.
- Follow sub-repo git boundaries and commit within the repo you changed.
- Default to feature-branch + pull-request workflow (avoid direct feature work on `main`/`master`).
- Ensure required checks and signoffs pass before merge actions.
- When you open a pull request, **send the PR link(s) to the user in this chat** (repo, branch, full URL) so they can review and merge. Do not rely on Slack for PR notification.
- Before merge, use **GitHub** mergeability and required checks; `CONFLICTING` or `DIRTY` state remains a blocker until fixed.
- Flag better dependency/tool options when they materially improve quality.
- Validate significant changes in Docker-oriented workflows to catch runtime-only issues early.

## Runtime Workflow Defaults

- On Linux in this workspace, prefer Podman-compatible container commands over Docker-specific assumptions.
- Prefer project-provided automation under `scripts/` for image setup, cleanup, build, and rebuild workflows before ad-hoc container commands.
- During multi-agent work, enforce single runtime ownership and script-based lifecycle checkpoints before and after testing batches.

## Scope Control

- Keep each task scoped to one subproject unless explicitly asked to span multiple.
- If work in one subproject requires changes in another, document a concrete handoff note or follow-up plan item instead of expanding scope mid-task.

## Source of Truth

- Live project files are authoritative over stale summaries.
- When instructions conflict, follow repository rules and current code state.
